statement.p:
If \mb{F} = F_1 \partial_1 + \cdots + F_n \partial_n is a conservative vector field on an open subset U of Euclidean space \mathbb{R}^n then 

                \frac{\partial F_i}{\partial x_j} = \frac{\partial F_j}{\partial x_i}

                for all 1 \leq i, j \leq n.

Let \mb{F} be a vector field defined on an open set U of \mathbb{R}^n. Then \mb{F} is conservative if and only if the vector line integral 

                \int_{\mathcal{C}} \mb{F} \cdot \tder{}{\mb{r}}

                on a smooth connected oriented curve in U depends only on its initial and terminal points.

proof.p:
If one assumes \mb{F} is conservative, then the fundamental theorem of line integrals immediately shows it is path independent. On the other hand, if it is path independent, for each connected component W of U, we choose a point \mb{a} \in W and define the function

            V (\mb{x} ) = \int_{P (\mb{x} )} \mb{F} \cdot \tder{}{\mb{r}}

            where P ( \mb{x}) is any path from \mb{a} to \mb{x}. Showing V is indeed a potential for \mb{F} is left as an exercise.
